---
import ElevationLayout from '../../layouts/ElevationLayout.astro';
import Hero from '../../components/elevation/Hero.astro';
import Section from '../../components/elevation/Section.astro';
import { getProductBySlug } from '../../lib/products/registry';
import { productJsonLd } from '../../lib/structured-data';

const product = getProductBySlug('governance-implementation-guide')!;
const jsonLd = productJsonLd(product, 'https://evoked.dev/products/governance-implementation-guide');
---

<ElevationLayout
  title="Agent Governance Implementation Guide"
  description="Add governance to the agent you already built. Step by step. Framework-specific. $9.99 PDF."
  structuredData={jsonLd}
>
  <Hero
    eyebrowParts={["Products", "Implementation guide"]}
    headline="Add governance to the agent you already built."
    metaphor={["Framework-specific. Step by step."]}
    sub="One session. No rewrite required."
  />

  <Section marker="FIG · I" heading="Why this guide">
    <p class="lede">
      You have an agent in production. It works. It does not have governance.
      You know it should - the scan told you that. This guide shows you how to
      add it without rewriting your system.
    </p>
    <p class="pd-body">
      25 pages. Framework-specific sections for CrewAI, LangGraph, and Pydantic AI.
      Code examples you can copy. From scan results to working governance in one
      sitting.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="FIG · II" heading="What you get">
    <div class="pd-features">
      <div class="pd-feature">
        <h3>The five properties</h3>
        <p>Identity, restraint, accountability, memory, and charter - implemented in order, with dependencies explained. Build them in the right sequence.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-feature">
        <h3>Framework-specific sections</h3>
        <p>CrewAI YAML configs. LangGraph state schemas. Pydantic AI tool definitions. Code that works in your stack, not generic advice.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-feature">
        <h3>Refusal implementation</h3>
        <p>Six refusal categories with real-world examples. How to build agents that know what they should not do - not just what they can.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-feature">
        <h3>Drift detection setup</h3>
        <p>Behavioral baselines, measurement cadence, and escalation thresholds. Know when your agent has changed before your users do.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-feature">
        <h3>EU AI Act mapping</h3>
        <p>Which governance properties map to which articles. The regulatory context for why this work matters beyond good engineering.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-feature">
        <h3>Verification step</h3>
        <p>Re-run the governance scan after implementation. See your score go from 1/5 to 5/5. Proof that the work landed.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="FIG · III" heading="Who this is for">
    <div class="pd-audience">
      <div class="pd-audience-card">
        <h3>Engineers with agents in production</h3>
        <p>Your agent works. This guide helps you make it governed. No rewrite required - governance layers onto existing architecture.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-audience-card">
        <h3>Teams adopting CrewAI, LangGraph, or Pydantic AI</h3>
        <p>Framework-specific guidance means you're not translating generic advice. The examples are in your stack's language.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-audience-card">
        <h3>Technical leads preparing for EU AI Act</h3>
        <p>Annex III obligations take effect 2 December 2027 under the May 2026 Digital Omnibus (revised from 2 August 2026; provisional political agreement pending Official Journal publication). Article 5 prohibitions and General-Purpose AI rules are live today. This guide maps governance properties to specific articles. Start now, not when the standards land.</p>
        <p class="pd-audience-fineprint"><em>Regulatory facts verified 2026-06-06.</em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="FIG · IV" heading="Buy the guide">
    <div class="pd-purchase">
      <div class="pd-price">$9.99</div>
      <p class="pd-purchase-lead">PDF download. 25 pages. Framework-specific implementation.</p>
      <a
        href={product.stripePaymentLink}
        class="pd-buy-cta"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener"
      >Get the Guide</a>
      <p class="pd-purchase-fineprint">
        Includes CrewAI, LangGraph, and Pydantic AI sections with code examples,
        the five-property implementation sequence, refusal categories, and EU AI
        Act mapping.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="NOTA · BENE" heading="Go deeper" closing={true}>
    <p class="lede">
      The guide gets governance into your codebase. If you need the complete
      practice, two doorways from here.
    </p>
    <div class="pd-upsell">
      <a href="/products/trust-architecture-complete" class="pd-upsell-card">
        <h3>Trust Architecture Complete ($149)</h3>
        <p>All four trust architecture products - identity, voice, governance, and restraint - in the order they should be built.</p>
        <span class="pd-upsell-link">View bundle &rarr;</span>
      </a>
      <a href="https://cal.com/cal.com-evoked/discovery-call" class="pd-upsell-card" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <h3>Governance Audit Engagement</h3>
        <p>We audit your agent system's governance architecture. Hands-on, in your codebase, with your team. Starting at $3,000.</p>
        <span class="pd-upsell-link">Book discovery call &rarr;</span>
      </a>
    </div>
  </Section>
</ElevationLayout>

<style>
  /* Page-local: card-level fineprint for the verified-on date stamp
     inside the EU-AI-Act-preparing audience card. */
  .pd-audience-fineprint {
    font-size: 0.78rem !important;
    color: var(--el-text-quiet) !important;
    margin-top: 0.5rem !important;
  }
</style>
